  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money appear to come from legitimate sources. This activity is illegal because it facilitates criminal enterprises by allowing them to \"clean\" their ill-gotten gains and integrate them into the legitimate financial system.\n\nIn many countries, including China, laws and regulations have been established to combat money laundering. For example, in China, the Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China was enacted to prevent money laundering activities, maintain the order of financial transactions, and safeguard the security of the economic and financial systems. The law requires financial institutions and specific non-financial institutions to establish and implement internal control systems, conduct customer due diligence, and report suspicious transactions.\n\nInternationally, organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) set global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorism financing (CTF) to promote coordinated international action against these illicit activities. Compliance with these standards is critical for countries to avoid negative impacts on their financial systems and international relations.",
